		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28378849">Germain, the vice president of a daily newspaper, and his bumbling assistant Carol are having a discussion on what would be the best place to begin the story. Who would be the most natural "main character" in a size of more than a dozen significant mafiosos? The story then shifts from cut scene to cut scene, tossing in a slick introduction of these characters as it jumps about seemingly randomly in events spanning over 200 years.<br />
<br />
Baccano! is one of the few works I feel can get by with its aggressive style. Its cast certainly lends itself to its own charisma. Every personality is simply so inviting, so suave and down right cool, that you can follow along the work's highly suspenseful plot without finding one of its many threads too "weak". (Yes I even like Jacuzzi, who grounds the cast and prevents it from being an assembly of "cool kids only".) And this I find astonishing. The whole narrative's structure is both engaging and finely paced. Baccano! is surprisingly intelligent in this manner: every character is allotted just the right amount of time, every scene is appropriately transitioned from, and every thread converges by the end. You have to hand it to Brains Base for that jazzy OST too.<br />
<br />
Neither does Baccano! suffer from its lack of characterization, or more generally from a "deeper" story—one of the few common criticisms of the work. One reason this is true is that the work ends before we need ask for more. Sorry we can't have <!--link--><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_o_notation" rel="nofollow">O(LOGH)</a> complexity in 13 episodes, when there's already limited time to sink into its trilinear narrative and its gargantuan cast. Baccano! also aims to be rather silly and over the top on occasion, but not ingratiatingly so; it doesn't stick to this one trait enough that it defines the series like other works do.<br />
<br />
Oh, also the novels are a fun read too, although not as engaging because of the crazy ride that the nonlinearity Brains Base added in does, or the fast-moving animation or music. I think Narita's light novels (or even the good-but-not-great 4 episode OVA) make you truly appreciate Baccano!'s pace. There's nothing quite like it.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
