		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28530991">As much as I enjoyed Baccano!, I couldn't help but be put off by the lack of distinction between characters.  Psychopath, while not a particularly common archetype in anime, is prevalent in the cast of Baccano!, even introducing more psychopaths in the Specials.  In addition to that, the first episode's confusing layout is also a point against it when it's so few episodes.<br />
<br />
That said, the VA in the dub is done well, the storyline is great, the action scenes are intense, and it's chock-full of non-sexual fan service for fans of anime like Black Lagoon, Trigun, etc.  The alchemic plot device adds a touch of supernatural, which helps the ridiculous nature of all the mafiosos be more believable and allow the viewer's suspension of disbelief encompass the entire story, which is greatly executed as well.  <br />
<br />
Despite the similarity between many of the characters, the cast is also large enough that a handful of characters are very different, each a breath of fresh air and always a joy to see.  The addition of these characters helps the other characters not to become stale.  The plot is also pushed by character interaction, which is important with a cast of this size and a setting as small as a train.  <br />
<br />
Overall, Baccano! is quite good, though flawed, and its directorial style is what I think sets it above other anime with similar execution or genre.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><span style="font-size: 80%;"><div style="text-align: center;"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://fc06.deviantart.net/fs42/f/2009/096/7/8/Tonberry_Banner_by_Doaj.jpg" /><br />
Vengeance of everyone's grudge.<!--size--></span><!--center--></div><br />
"I didn't add it to my list so I forgot I was watching that." - lpf</div></td>
