		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28550287">There's certainly reasons why. One of the advantages I see in forgoing linearity is that if you simply follow the events chronologically, you don't nearly see how significant certain events are without going to another of the 3 timelines instead. This makes it more engaging particularly. Second, there is also the intrigue in following seemingly tangential related plot threads only to see why they're related in the future. Pretty much the "ahah!" reaction lpf pointed out. Third, it also makes sense on the cast level, because jumpin among different timelines is very much like jumping from different character POvs within one time frame. This allows for more novelty when dealing with a particular mystery, for example, where you see a brutal death scene from one person's POV, and then you see the exact same thing from another's. Fourth, it makes the show intentionally silly and more self-aware, just as the premiere episode leads you into viewing the story as a story in and of itself.<br />
<br />
@needs themes to be better than "merely good": That's totally up to you, and maybe even worthy of a Topic discussion. As you can expect, I don't find this to be true at all, as themes are complementary but not necessarily primary to fiction.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
