		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser28563893" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/xeroborn"><strong>xeroborn</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/xeroborn"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/3308821.jpg" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: Oct 2013<br>
		  Posts: 81
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message28563893">Storytelling is something I take very seriously (I spend much of my free time writing screenplays, novels, etc). It is my opinion that when you set out to tell a story you should have a reason for doing so, a theme. This is what creates resonate, lasting works. <br />
<br />
I understand the storytelling advantages to using a non-linear structure, but that's not really what I meant. <br />
<br />
Let me try to explain both of these points by bringing Kara no Kyoukai (KnK) into the discussion. I will try to be as non-spoilery as possible, because this is not a KnK thread.  <br />
<br />
KnK uses a similiar non-linear structure as Baccano. However, there is a clear reason why this was done. Its like the author sat down and thought of his theme, and then his characters to represent that theme, and then what structure would present his theme in as clear and powerful a way as possible.<br />
<br />
The central question/mystery of KnK becomes why are these characters doing such horrible things, and allowing such horrible things to be done to them. The sheer power of the catharsis moment is like a gut-punch. The 'ahah!' moment as you put it (and in KnK its more like a jaw-dropping, take your breath away, full-on goosebump moment), serves just one purpose: to highlight the characters, and as characters are extensions of theme, the theme. <br />
<br />
So, Baccano did not have the same effect on me, and I have to ask, why?  Because the 'ahah!' moments didn't mean anything. I finished the show last night, and have had some time to think about it now. I see issues with the plot (relating mostly to creating tension), and with the characters. I can go into that later maybe, but this post is already long enough.<br />
<br />
I think the reason why I tend to appreciate a well-articulated theme in media is because its so damn hard to do. If it was easy, every story would have one, and we would not be having this conversation. But its not easy, its incredibly difficult. And when its presented in such a powerful way as KnK it is memorable and displays extraordinary skill and craft. <br />
<br />
Not every series is capable of this, or even aspires to this, which is fine. Baccano is an exercise in style, and a relatively successful one at that, but nothing more.  If that's all you wanted, you probably really enjoyed the series. To me, it was underwhelming.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by xeroborn, 02-14-14, 1:06 PM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
